			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=109761&amp;sid=3e422e7eab686d0b2e399c3d21ccacf7#109761"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Wed Mar 16, 2005 9:34 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Apache2 web server and security</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=109761&amp;sid=3e422e7eab686d0b2e399c3d21ccacf7"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>     </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I need something more than a "is this port active" monitor.
<br />

<br />
Ideally we need good service monitoring. <ul><li>If I monitor an Oracle database, I want the monitor to verify the database instances are up, and even run a query to verify it, and validate the data coming back is sane.<li>If I monitor an apache webserver serving a java application, I want the monitor to log in to the application with a username/password and verify the data coming back is what is expected from that application.<li>Basically, every service the box provides gets verified, not just trivially touched on. Otherwise there's really no point in doing the monitoring. Most monitor software is hardly more competent than ping in this respect.</ul>Then we need good trending information.
<br />
Collect and graph information about the following, for starters...<ul><li>Utilization for CPUs, Memory, Disks, Networks, preferably fine grained<li>User login, duration, total number of commands issued<li>Full security audits, lists of anything changed, verification of permissions, changes of config files<li>Robust trigger architecture, triggering on any state change, trend threshold, or event that can be monitored<li>Unified logging service, able to combine unix/linux and windows logs (master syslog server)<li>Diverse notification architecture, supporting email, pagers, IM/Text, etc<li>Support for <span style="font-style: italic">all</span> features under Linux, Solaris, Windows</ul>And then we get into actually visualizing the data...<ul><li>Decent GUI (preferably web based) with fully customizeable views<li>Ability to display all logged information from system logs across all architectures in ONE format<li>Time-based trending views, at least daily/weekly/monthly/quarterly/yearly<li>A tray-resident notification app with popups to notify the logged in user instantly of state changes</ul>Of course, then we need some level of network awareness in the monitor. If a router to Building Z goes up in smoke, the network monitor application should be intelligent to know that the reason the 70 hosts in Building Z are no longer reporting isn't because they ALL went down (giving me 70 seperate emails/pages), but that the router went down and the building is no longer accessible. 
<br />

<br />
The ability to monitor firewalls, switches, routers, printers, uninterruptible power supplies, network KVMs, and any other network attached devices would also be a big plus.
<br />

<br />
I don't know of any package that can handle that. Any open source solution requires days of setup work and testing (these are mission critical boxes, you can't just add monitoring agents to them on a whim). They also require you to write a truckload of scripts to do the work and simplify any failures down to a single return code. That's fine for an expert administrator. I'd prefer to have it be the kind of thing an intermediate could set up... preferably by dragging widgets around inside a web interface. Apparently no company has stepped up to the challenge of writing something like that. 
<br />

<br />
If you know a server name, database instance name, login, password, one basic query, and valid return data, you should be able to set up the monitoring of that oracle service using nothing but the mouse. Ditto for any service. The company should provide the necessary scripts and they should be versatile to handle anything thrown at them. All they'd need is a public form; people will write the scripts as plugins for them.
<br />

<br />
I dunno, maybe my standards are just too high. Seems to be a problem I have...<br />
				<span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by EvilNight on Wed Mar 16, 2005 9:38 pm; edited 3 times in total</span><br />
